To terminate a C program, you can use the exit() function. This function takes an integer as an argument, which is the status code that is returned to the operating system. The default status code is 0, which means the program terminated normally. If you want to terminate the program with an error, you can pass a non-zero status code. For example, if you want to terminate the program with an error, you can use the following code:

```c
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // Your code here
    exit(1); // Terminate the program with an error
    return 0;
}
```

In this example, the program will terminate with a status code of 1, indicating that an error occurred.
